Hi all,

this series introduces ipxlat, a virtual netdevice implementing stateless
IPv4/IPv6 translation. The intent is to provide a small in-kernel
translator for environments where IPv4-only and IPv6-only segments must
interoperate. The implementation follows:

- RFC 7915 for SIIT behavior
- RFC 6052 for address mapping
- RFC 4884 for ICMP extension handling in error payloads

The series contains 14 patches covering driver core, translation paths,
netlink API and selftests.

ipxlat sits at a boundary between two kernel models. It is exposed as a
netdevice, so it has device semantics such as MTU and netdev statistics. At
the same time, most of its work is protocol translation logic that is
closer to stack processing than to a conventional L2/L3 forwarding device.
The implementation therefore uses netdevice hooks for integration and
lifecycle, while translation behavior follows RFC rules and reuses existing
IP stack helpers for routing, fragmentation and checksum handling.

Feedback on the netdevice integration model is welcome, but this series
intentionally keeps scope limited to a self-contained driver to make review
and validation tractable.

ipxlat devices are created and destroyed via rtnl link operations.
Per-device translation parameters are configured through a generic netlink
family named ipxlat. The current configuration includes xlat-prefix6 and
lowest_ipv6_mtu. In practice, xlat-prefix6 defines the RFC6052 mapping prefix and
lowest_ipv6_mtu is a configured floor for the 4 to 6 pre-fragmentation
threshold, independent of the device MTU.

The implementation enforces a strict processing contract: packet validation
is done once, then translation runs on that validated layout. When
translation cannot continue, the packet is either dropped or redirected to
translator ICMP emission depending on RFC-required behavior for that
failure class.

Control-plane updates are serialized, while the data path reads
configuration locklessly to keep per-packet overhead low. During live
reconfiguration, readers may transiently observe mixed old and new values;
this may cause a small number of packet drops while configuration is being
changed. This tradeoff is intentional to keep the fast path simple and
lightweight.

Selftests are added under tools/testing/selftests/net/ipxlat and cover
ICMP, TCP and UDP translation in both directions, large-packet and
fragmentation-sensitive paths, ICMP error translation, and PMTUD-related
emission paths.

No generic networking core behavior is changed. The series is contained to
the new driver, its uapi header, netlink specification and selftests.

Thanks for your review.
